{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_1","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' ROADMAP.md && printf '\\\\n---MAILBOX-PLAN---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,240p' task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md && printf '\\\\n---RELATED-PLAN---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,220p' task-plans/claude-codex-team-space-task-plan.md && printf '\\\\n---ACTIVE-PLAN---\\\\n' && sed -n '1,220p' .claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md && printf '\\\\n---LATEST-NOTES---\\\\n' && for f in \"'$(ls -1t .claude/plans/loloop/evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-*.md | head -n 2); do echo \"--- $f ---\"; sed -n '\"'1,220p' \\\"\"'$f\"; done'","aggregated_output":"# Codex-Managed-Agent Long-Range Roadmap\n\nThis roadmap is the spine. It should stay short.\n\nUse it to answer:\n\n- what the main milestones are\n- what order we should execute them in\n- which task-plan file owns the concrete work\n\nDetailed work belongs in `task-plans/*.md`.\n\n## North Star\n\nMake `Codex-Managed-Agent` a dependable VS Code control surface for multi-thread Codex work:\n\n- stable enough for daily use\n- structured enough to keep evolving\n- fast enough to feel responsive\n- clear enough that new features do not collapse back into one giant file\n\n## Product Principles\n\n- **One interactive board**\n- **Server-aware, not server-fragile**\n- **Small, composable host modules**\n- **Board first, chrome second**\n- **Persistent memory**\n\n## Milestones\n\n## Milestone Status\n\n- [x] Milestone 1 — Architecture Stabilization\n- [x] Milestone 2 — Board Interaction Quality\n- [x] Milestone 3 — Insight and Guidance Layer\n- [x] Milestone 4 — Operational Reliability\n- [x] Milestone 5 — Publishable Product Quality\n\n### Milestone 1 — Architecture Stabilization\n\nGoal:\n\n- keep the extension modular and reviewable\n\nRelated plans:\n\n- host/module cleanup is already largely completed\n- continue only when new architectural drift appears\n\n### Milestone 2 — Board Interaction Quality\n\nGoal:\n\n- make board interaction intentional, smooth, and predictable\n\nPrimary plan:\n\n- `task-plans/board-interaction-quality-task-plan.md`\n\n### Milestone 3 — Insight and Guidance Layer\n\nGoal:\n\n- make the extension useful as memory and workflow guidance, not only a launcher\n\nPrimary plan:\n\n- `task-plans/insight-and-guidance-task-plan.md`\n\n### Milestone 4 — Operational Reliability\n\nGoal:\n\n- make loop, background continue, and Codex visibility control trustworthy\n\nPrimary plans:\n\n- `task-plans/operational-reliability-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/codex-visibility-control-task-plan.md`\n\n### Milestone 5 — Publishable Product Quality\n\nGoal:\n\n- keep releases understandable, repeatable, and maintainable\n\nRelated plans:\n\n- release and doc quality work should stay aligned with the current architecture and priority docs\n\n## Delivery Order\n\n### Priority 1 — Must Stabilize First\n\n- `task-plans/board-interaction-quality-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/operational-reliability-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/codex-visibility-control-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/cma-codex-communication-optimization-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/codex-loop-control-surface-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/cross-path-unified-management-task-plan.md`\n\n### Priority 2 — Workflow Multipliers\n\n- `task-plans/prompt-rule-memo-cards-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/insight-and-guidance-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/no-editor-first-workflows-task-plan.md`\n\n### Priority 3 — Multi-Agent Expansion\n\n- `task-plans/codex-multi-agent-coordination-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/claude-codex-team-space-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`\n\n### Priority 4 — Ecosystem Extensions\n\n- `task-plans/wechat-bot-background-service-task-plan.md`\n- `task-plans/html-ppt-visual-extensions-task-plan.md`\n\n## Working Rule\n\nWhen new work appears:\n\n1. decide which priority bucket it belongs to\n2. attach it to an existing `task-plan` if possible\n3. create a new `task-plan` only when the work introduces a new delivery track\n4. keep `ROADMAP.md` as the index, not the implementation dump\n\n## Task-Plan Formatting Rule\n\nWhen creating or updating files under `task-plans/`:\n\n1. put a `Status: planned`, `Status: active`, or `Status: complete` line directly below the title\n2. write task items as Markdown checkboxes using `[ ]` and `[x]`\n3. when work is completed, mark the relevant checkbox items as `[x]`\n4. when a task-plan is fully completed, set its top status line to `Status: complete`\n5. when adding new task items later, add them in the same checkbox format instead of plain bullets\n\n## Immediate Focus\n\nCore roadmap milestones are currently complete.\n\nImmediate follow-on track:\n\n- `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`\n\nCurrent handoff state:\n\n- `task-plans/prompt-rule-memo-cards-task-plan.md` is complete.\n- Keep the mailbox loop track active first so team-mode planning, prompt alignment, and non-destructive defaults are stabilized before reopening broader coordination expansion.\n\n---MAILBOX-PLAN---\n# Codex Team Mailbox Loop Task Plan\n\nStatus: active\n\n## Priority\n\nPriority 3\n\n## Objective\n\nTurn the current early mailbox prototype into a dependable `codex-loop`-driven team-coordination track without breaking existing single-thread, board, loop, or dashboard workflows.\n\n## Scope\n\n- mailbox-backed multi-thread coordination under `.codex-team/`\n- `codex-loop` plan, prompt, and handoff assets for this track\n- non-destructive UI surfacing for team state inside the existing dashboard\n- bounded defaults for loop automation with a 1 minute interval\n- repo-facing plan hygiene and git-safe slicing guidance\n\n## Rules\n\n- [x] add new team-mode capabilities as opt-in enhancements, not replacements for current flows\n- [x] do not regress existing thread lifecycle, board interactions, auto-continue, or loop controls\n- [x] keep mailbox state isolated from legacy board/tab metadata so rollback stays easy\n- [ ] keep implementation sliced into small commits; avoid mixing protocol, UI, and refactor churn in one commit\n- [x] require at least one review-oriented loop in every two-loop window to audit progress, detect drift, and adjust the active plan if work is heading in a bad direction\n- [x] treat version safety as a standing gate: if a slice risks breaking the current stable behavior, stop expanding scope and steer the next loop toward rollback, isolation, or plan correction first\n\n## Task 1 — Loop-Owned Planning Surface\n\n- [x] create and maintain one mailbox-specific task-plan as the long-form source of truth\n- [x] point `.claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md` at this plan with one bounded current slice\n- [x] align `.codex-loop/prompt.md` so recurring passes stay anchored to this mailbox track\n- [x] write one evolution note per bounded slice and keep the next handoff minimal\n- [x] record whether each loop is an execution loop or an analysis loop so progress audits stay explicit\n\n## Task 2 — Mailbox Protocol Stabilization\n\n- [ ] define the minimal on-disk mailbox schema for `tasks/`, `events/`, `inbox/`, `agents/`, and `team.md`\n- [ ] keep task states explicit: `queued`, `assigned`, `running`, `blocked`, `review`, `completed`, `failed`, `stale`\n- [ ] ensure every write path uses deterministic ids and append-only event behavior where possible\n- [ ] make restart recovery rely on mailbox files instead of inferred free text\n\n## Task 3 — Supervisor and Worker Flow\n\n- [ ] keep supervisor actions explicit: initialize, assign, inspect, recover, and handoff\n- [ ] support worker actions as mailbox events only: claim, heartbeat, blocked, complete\n- [ ] attach a result envelope shape to completion events so future automation can inspect outcomes\n- [ ] define stale-lease recovery behavior before adding background reclamation automation\n\n## Task 4 — Non-Destructive Dashboard Surface\n\n- [x] surface mailbox summary in overview without reshaping existing overview cards\n- [x] expose thread-level team controls only inside bounded surfaces such as the drawer\n- [x] avoid overloading current board tab semantics with team routing semantics\n- [x] make the team surface clearly secondary when mailbox mode is not initialized\n\n## Task 5 — Loop Automation Defaults\n\n- [x] set the default loop interval for this repo to 1 minute\n- [x] keep custom interval input available for manual override\n- [x] keep daemon start/restart commands backward compatible with existing state files\n- [x] ensure the default quick-start affordance reads as `Loop 1m` instead of `Loop 10m`\n\n## Task 6 — Validation and Hardening\n\n- [ ] syntax-check touched host and webview modules after each bounded slice\n- [x] verify that opening the dashboard still works when no team space exists\n- [x] verify that mailbox actions do not change legacy thread status unless explicitly intended\n- [ ] reject stale or non-existent thread ids before mailbox actions write `.codex-team` task or agent state, using `panel.lastPayload.dashboard.threads` as the source of truth\n- [ ] implement one shared live-thread resolver from `panel.lastPayload.dashboard.threads` and use it only in `assignTaskToThread`, `claimTaskForThread`, `heartbeatThread`, `blockTaskForThread`, and `completeTaskForThread`\n- [x] verify that a stopped or missing loop daemon still renders cleanly\n- [x] on every analysis loop, review the last two iterations for regressions, incomplete work, or plan drift before approving the next execution slice\n- [ ] if an analysis loop finds risk to the current stable version, prioritize containment, revert-friendly isolation, or follow-up hardening before adding new behavior\n\n## Task 7 — Git and Delivery Hygiene\n\n- [ ] keep commits bounded and reviewable\n- [ ] use commit shapes such as `feat(team-mailbox): ...` and `docs(loop): ...`\n- [ ] avoid sweeping refactors until mailbox behavior is stable\n- [ ] document any required follow-up migration before replacing existing behavior\n\n## Exit Criteria\n\n- mailbox coordination is plan-driven through `codex-loop`\n- the default loop cadence for this track is 1 minute\n- team-mode behavior is visibly available but remains opt-in\n- existing extension features remain usable without mailbox initialization\n\n---RELATED-PLAN---\n# Claude Codex Team Space Task Plan\n\n## Priority\n\nPriority 3\n\n## Objective\n\nExpand from Codex-only control into a provider-aware agent team workspace.\n\n## Scope\n\n- Claude + Codex shared board\n- provider-aware role separation\n- collaboration model across providers\n\n## Tasks\n\n### Task 1 — Provider Abstraction\n\n- define provider-neutral thread/task concepts\n- keep provider-specific actions isolated\n\n### Task 2 — Shared Team Surface\n\n- decide how Codex and Claude entities coexist in one board or team space\n- keep visual semantics clear across providers\n\n### Task 3 — Role and Ownership Model\n\n- define how work is split between providers\n- avoid pretending provider internals are fully controllable\n\n## Constraints\n\nOfficial provider plugins do not expose full internal APIs. This phase must be designed as coordination, not total provider control.\n\n## Exit Criteria\n\n- a realistic shared team-space model exists\n- the design respects provider boundaries\n\n---ACTIVE-PLAN---\n# ACTIVE_PLAN\n\nTrack Status: active\n\n## Milestone Status\n\n- [x] Milestone 1 — Architecture Stabilization\n- [x] Milestone 2 — Board Interaction Quality\n- [x] Milestone 3 — Insight and Guidance Layer\n- [x] Milestone 4 — Operational Reliability\n- [x] Milestone 5 — Publishable Product Quality\n\n## Current Task Plan\n\n- `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`\n\n## Current Slice\n\n- [ ] Task 6 slice — add one shared host-side live-thread resolver before mailbox actions write `.codex-team` task or agent state.\n\n## Next Handoff\n\n- Run the mailbox track on a 1 minute loop unless the user explicitly overrides it.\n- Treat 1 minute as the canonical cadence; earlier 10 minute and 2 minute mailbox notes are historical drift, not the current source of truth.\n- Keep the audit result fixed: Task 4 is now effectively closed in code, the no-team-space dashboard path plus the missing-loop-daemon render path are already verified, and mailbox write paths are already isolated from legacy thread-status mutations.\n- Keep the planning result fixed: no further plan-shaping analysis is needed before the next bounded execution slice.\n- Keep the review-window result fixed: the newest two mailbox analysis loops, including the legacy-status isolation closure, found no new regression or drift beyond the already-scoped resolver slice.\n- Keep the review-window bookkeeping fixed: the current two-loop analysis requirement is refreshed and satisfied for this mailbox handoff state.\n- Keep the analysis discipline result fixed: the mailbox track now has an established two-loop review pattern recorded in task-plan and loloop notes, so the remaining Task 6 gap is execution hardening rather than review-process setup.\n- Keep the rule-level review result fixed: the mailbox task plan now reflects that the two-loop review rule is already established process, not an open planning gap.\n- Keep the rule-level safety result fixed: the mailbox task plan now reflects that containment-first version safety is established process, not an open planning gap.\n- Keep the rule-level isolation result fixed: the mailbox task plan now reflects that mailbox state stays isolated from legacy board/tab metadata, so rollback remains straightforward.\n- Keep the rule-level opt-in result fixed: the mailbox task plan now reflects that team-mode surfaces remain additive and secondary, not replacements for existing single-thread flows.\n- Keep the rule-level non-regression result fixed: the mailbox task plan now reflects that current mailbox work has stayed non-destructive across thread lifecycle, board interaction, auto-continue, and loop-control surfaces.\n- Keep the rule-layer cleanup result fixed: for the current mailbox scope, rule-level process and safety debt is effectively closed; remaining unresolved work is execution hardening plus later delivery hygiene.\n- Keep the analysis-convergence result fixed: further analysis-only repo edits are no longer justified unless a new regression or containment need appears.\n- Keep the post-convergence result fixed: repeated analysis after convergence has not surfaced any new regression, so the remaining critical-path work is still the Task 6 resolver slice.\n- Keep the post-convergence discipline fixed: analysis-only mailbox passes should stop mutating task-plan or active-plan scope unless a new regression, drift signal, or containment need appears.\n- Keep the forced-analysis discipline fixed: if a caller keeps requiring another analysis-only mailbox pass without new evidence, limit repo edits to a minimal handoff refresh and preserve the same execution target.\n- Keep the repeated-analysis refresh discipline fixed: when such a minimal refresh is unavoidable, only restate the same Task 6 resolver handoff instead of reopening task-plan scope or adding new mailbox branches.\n- Keep the unchanged-handoff summary fixed: without new regression, drift, or containment evidence, repeated analysis-only mailbox passes are bookkeeping only; they must not create new scope, branches, boundaries, or targets, and the same Task 6 resolver slice remains the only actionable next step until execution changes the state.\n- Keep the active-plan dedup result fixed: now that the unchanged-handoff state is summarized once, later analysis-only passes should preserve that compressed handoff shape unless new evidence requires a real plan change.\n- Keep the active-plan growth guard fixed: analysis-only mailbox passes should not grow `ACTIVE_PLAN.md` again unless a new regression, drift signal, or containment requirement creates a materially different handoff.\n- Keep the active-plan edit floor fixed: when no new evidence exists, any forced analysis-only update to `ACTIVE_PLAN.md` should stay at the level of a minimal guard or bookkeeping line and must not change the substantive Task 6 handoff.\n- Keep the active-plan substantive freeze fixed: absent new evidence, later analysis-only mailbox passes should leave the substantive Task 6 handoff block unchanged and only record stability, not reshape the plan.\n- Keep the analysis-only stability record fixed: when the mailbox review window stays clean, future analysis-only passes should record that stability and preserve the same hardening handoff rather than inventing fresh planning work.\n- Keep the same-handoff carry-through fixed: when the review window stays clean, repeated analysis-only passes should continue carrying the same Task 6 handoff forward instead of generating alternate mailbox directions.\n- Keep the stable hardening path fixed: when no new evidence appears, the mailbox track should continue pointing at the same hardening-first Task 6 resolver slice and should not reopen broader mailbox planning.\n- Keep the stable next-step result fixed: when the review window stays clean, the next useful step should remain the same bounded Task 6 resolver slice rather than a new analysis-only planning branch.\n- Keep the bounded-target result fixed: when no new evidence appears, repeated analysis-only passes should keep the Task 6 resolver slice narrowly bounded instead of broadening the target surface.\n- Keep the sole-hardening-target result fixed: when the review window stays clean, the Task 6 resolver slice should remain the sole bounded hardening target instead of splitting into parallel mailbox follow-ups.\n- Keep the sole-remaining-gap result fixed: when the review window stays clean, the only remaining bounded gap should still be the Task 6 resolver slice plus its follow-up syntax check.\n- Keep the remaining-work equivalence fixed: when no new evidence appears, any description of the remaining mailbox work should resolve back to the same Task 6 resolver slice plus syntax check, not a new parallel gap.\n- Keep the same-gap anchor fixed: when the review window stays clean, the unresolved mailbox hardening work should remain anchored to the same Task 6 resolver slice rather than being reframed as a different target.\n- Keep the same-gap identity fixed: when the review window stays clean, the remaining mailbox hardening work should keep the same Task 6 resolver identity instead of being renamed or broadened.\n- Keep the audit freeze fixed: further analysis passes should not change the resolver execution target unless a new regression or containment need appears.\n- Keep the resolver spec fixed: no further analysis narrowing is needed beyond `panel.lastPayload.dashboard.threads` unless a real regression or containment need appears.\n- Keep the remaining-gap result fixed: with no containment trigger in the current review window, the only unresolved Task 6 work is the live-thread resolver pair plus the syntax-check step that follows the future code change.\n- Keep the next pass hardening-first: execute the remaining Task 6 stale-thread validation work in `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md` by adding one shared live-thread resolver in `src/host/team-coordination.js`, sourcing it from `panel.lastPayload.dashboard.threads`, and using it only in `assignTaskToThread`, `claimTaskForThread`, `heartbeatThread`, `blockTaskForThread`, and `completeTaskForThread`.\n- Keep the execution boundary fixed: do not expand that slice into mailbox UI changes, stale-lease recovery, or broader supervisor flow changes.\n- Keep the closure rule fixed: the resolver slice should close both Task 6 thread-validation checkboxes together, because the resolver is the concrete implementation of the stale-thread rejection outcome.\n- If the hardening pass finds risk to current stable behavior, pause feature expansion and route the following pass to containment or rollback-friendly isolation.\n\n---LATEST-NOTES---\n--- .claude/plans/loloop/evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-same-gap-identity.md ---\n## Loop Type\n\n- type: analysis\n\n## What Changed\n\n- Audited the latest mailbox review window and found no new lifecycle, board/tab, cadence, or task-plan/code regression.\n- Added one explicit same-gap-identity line in `ACTIVE_PLAN.md` so evidence-free analysis passes keep the unresolved mailbox hardening work identified as the same Task 6 resolver slice.\n\n## Plan\n\n- Active plan: `.claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md`\n- Current milestone: follow-on track — `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`\n- Bounded target: keep the remaining mailbox hardening work identified as the same resolver slice during another analysis-only pass\n\n## Review Window\n\n- reviewed loops: `evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-remaining-work-equivalence.md` and `evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-same-gap-anchor.md`\n- status: analysis complete; next slice should stay hardening-first\n\n## Analysis Checks\n\n- legacy thread lifecycle safety: unchanged. No new lifecycle mutation risk appeared in the reviewed window.\n- board/tab semantic safety: unchanged. No new routing or dashboard regression appeared in the reviewed window.\n- loop-only cadence impact: unchanged and aligned at 1 minute.\n- task-plan/code alignment: stable. The only remaining actionable work is still the Task 6 resolver pair plus syntax check.\n- next slice decision: yes, hardening-first. The next execution slice should still add one shared live-thread resolver before mailbox writes.\n\n## Next Handoff\n\n- Follow `.claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md`\n- Execute one hardening-first slice: add one shared live-thread resolver from `panel.lastPayload.dashboard.threads`, close the remaining stale-thread validation pair, and run the Task 6 syntax check after the code change\n--- .claude/plans/loloop/evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-same-gap-anchor.md ---\n## Loop Type\n\n- type: analysis\n\n## What Changed\n\n- Audited the latest mailbox review window and found no new lifecycle, board/tab, cadence, or task-plan/code regression.\n- Added one explicit same-gap-anchor line in `ACTIVE_PLAN.md` so evidence-free analysis passes keep the unresolved mailbox hardening work anchored to the same Task 6 resolver slice.\n\n## Plan\n\n- Active plan: `.claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md`\n- Current milestone: follow-on track — `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`\n- Bounded target: keep the remaining mailbox hardening work anchored to the same resolver slice during another analysis-only pass\n\n## Review Window\n\n- reviewed loops: `evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-sole-remaining-gap.md` and `evolution-2026-04-16-mailbox-remaining-work-equivalence.md`\n- status: analysis complete; next slice should stay hardening-first\n\n## Analysis Checks\n\n- legacy thread lifecycle safety: unchanged. No new lifecycle mutation risk appeared in the reviewed window.\n- board/tab semantic safety: unchanged. No new routing or dashboard regression appeared in the reviewed window.\n- loop-only cadence impact: unchanged and aligned at 1 minute.\n- task-plan/code alignment: stable. The only remaining actionable work is still the Task 6 resolver pair plus syntax check.\n- next slice decision: yes, hardening-first. The next execution slice should still add one shared live-thread resolver before mailbox writes.\n\n## Next Handoff\n\n- Follow `.claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md`\n- Execute one hardening-first slice: add one shared live-thread resolver from `panel.lastPayload.dashboard.threads`, close the remaining stale-thread validation pair, and run the Task 6 syntax check after the code change\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
